   "source": [
    "# SoundScape -Jasmeh Gill\n",
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "SoundScape is an ocean noise pollution simulator built using Pygame. It visualizes how shipping noise affects whale \n",
    "migration by modeling acoustic transmission loss in real time. Players drag ships away from whale lanes and slow them \n",
    "down to reduce noise exposure before the whales strand.\n",
    "\n",
    "The simulation is built on the NOAA underwater acoustic transmission loss formula:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$TL = 20 \\cdot \\log_{10}(r) + \\alpha \\cdot r$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where \\\\(r\\\\) is distance in meters and \\\\(\\\\alpha = 0.0008\\\\) dB/m is the absorption coefficient for low-frequency \n",
    "shipping noise. Every whale calculates its total noise exposure every frame using this formula, and that number \n",
    "drives the entire stress and behavior system."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Import Section"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pygame\n",
    "import math\n",
    "import random\n",
    "import sys"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Initializing Pygame"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "pygame.init()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Window and Layout Constants\n",
    "\n",
    "The window is split into two sections. The left 700 pixels is the ocean simulation panel where ships and whales move. \n",
    "The right side is the information panel showing live noise readings, stress bars, and controls. \n",
    "OCEAN_W defines the boundary between them."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "width, height = 1500, 750\n",
    "win = pygame.display.set_mode((width, height))\n",
    "pygame.display.set_caption(\"SoundScape\")\n",
    "\n",
    "OCEAN_W = 700  # ocean panel width -- everything else is the info panel\n",
    "\n",
    "FPS = 60"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Whale Lanes and Ship Starting Positions\n",
    "\n",
    "WHALE_LANES defines the three horizontal y-positions that whale pods travel along. \n",
    "SHIP_STARTS defines where the five ships begin. Three of the five starting positions overlap with whale lanes \n",
    "intentionally -- that is the core problem the player has to solve by dragging ships away."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "WHALE_LANES = [115, 325, 535]  # y positions of the 3 migration routes\n",
    "SHIP_STARTS = [100, 220, 325, 470, 610]  # 3 of these overlap whale lanes intentionally"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Colors and Fonts\n",
    "\n",
    "The color palette uses a warm teal and amber scheme instead of a standard blue ocean palette. \n",
    "AMBER is used for ships that have been slowed down, TEAL for whale routes, and the GREEN/YELLOW/RED \n",
    "progression is used for the stress bars. Four font sizes are defined for different UI elements."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "OCEAN   = (8,  48, 66)\n",
    "PANEL   = (14, 22, 34)\n",
    "AMBER   = (215, 158, 44)\n",
    "TEAL    = (75, 158, 118)\n",
    "WHITE   = (228, 222, 205)\n",
    "GRAY    = (118, 114, 102)\n",
    "GREEN   = (58,  178, 115)\n",
    "YELLOW  = (210, 165, 40)\n",
    "RED     = (198, 55,  46)\n",
    "FOAM    = (155, 205, 195)\n",
    "\n",
    "font1 = pygame.font.SysFont(\"Trebuchet MS\", 21, bold=True)# big values\n",
    "font2 = pygame.font.SysFont(\"Trebuchet MS\", 15)# medium\n",
    "font3 = pygame.font.SysFont(\"Trebuchet MS\", 12)# small labels\n",
    "font4 = pygame.font.SysFont(\"Trebuchet MS\", 11, bold=True)# key badges"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Ocean Background\n",
    "\n",
    "Drawing a gradient background by looping through every row of pixels is expensive if done every frame. \n",
    "Instead, the background is rendered once into a Pygame Surface at startup, then blitted to the screen each frame. \n",
    "This significantly improves performance since blitting a pre-rendered surface is much faster than redrawing it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ocean_bg = pygame.Surface((OCEAN_W, height))\n",
    "for y in range(height):\n",
    "    f = y / height\n",
    "    pygame.draw.line(ocean_bg, (int(8+f*5), int(48+f*16), int(66+f*7)), (0, y), (OCEAN_W, y))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Acoustic Physics Function\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the core of the simulation. The NOAA underwater acoustic transmission loss formula calculates \n",
    "how many decibels of noise a receiver picks up at a given distance from a source.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$TL = 20 \\cdot \\log_{10}(r) + \\alpha \\cdot r$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The first term \\\\(20 \\cdot \\log_{10}(r)\\\\) represents spherical spreading -- sound radiates outward in all directions \n",
    "and naturally gets quieter with distance. The second term \\\\(\\alpha \\cdot r\\\\) represents absorption -- water \n",
    "absorbs some acoustic energy as the sound travels through it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def received_db(source_db, dist_px):\n",
    "    m = max(1.0, dist_px * 10)# 1 pixel = 10 meters\n",
    "    tl = 20 * math.log10(m) + 0.0008 * m # transmission loss formula\n",
    "    return max(0.0, source_db - tl)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Ship Class\n",
    "\n",
    "The Ship class represents a cargo vessel traveling from the top of the screen to the bottom. \n",
    "The most important attribute is lane, which is the ship's permanent horizontal position. \n",
    "When the player drags a ship, lane updates to the new position. The ship's x coordinate then \n",
    "smoothly slides toward lane each frame, creating the sliding animation. Because lane updates \n",
    "permanently, the ship respawns at the new position on every subsequent pass.\n",
    "\n",
    "The slot parameter staggers starting y positions so ships don't all enter the screen at the same time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Ship:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, x, slot=0, start_y=None):\n",
    "        self.lane = float(x)# permanent x position -- player changes this by dragging\n",
    "        self.x= float(x)\n",
    "        self.y= float(start_y if start_y is not None else -80 - slot * 55)\n",
    "        self.speed= 0.7 + (slot % 3) * 0.15\n",
    "        self.base_speed = self.speed\n",
    "        self.is_slow= False\n",
    "        self.being_dragged= False\n",
    "        self.wake_trail= []\n",
    "        self.finished= False"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Ship Noise Level\n",
    "\n",
    "Ship noise is not constant -- it depends on speed. Slower propellers produce less cavitation, \n",
    "which is the main source of shipping noise. This is modeled as a linear relationship between \n",
    "speed ratio and noise output. At full speed (ratio = 1.0), the ship produces 168 dB. \n",
    "When slowed to 28% of base speed, the ratio drops to 0.28, and noise falls to around 101 dB. \n",
    "This is why clicking to slow a ship is an effective player action."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "@property\n",
    "def noise_db(self):\n",
    "    speed_ratio = self.speed / self.base_speed\n",
    "    return 168.0 * (0.60 + 0.40 * speed_ratio)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Calculating Danger Radius\n",
    "\n",
    "The danger radius is the pixel distance at which this ship's noise drops to exactly 118 dB, which is the \n",
    "whale masking threshold. Below 118 dB, whale communication is unaffected. Above it, whales begin to lose \n",
    "navigation ability.\n",
    "\n",
    "Solving the transmission loss equation analytically for r is difficult because of the alpha term, so binary \n",
    "search is used instead. The search converges on the correct radius in 15 iterations, which is fast enough \n",
    "to run every frame. The noise rings drawn around each ship use this value as their maximum radius."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def get_danger_radius(self):\n",
    "    lo, hi = 1.0, 450.0\n",
    "    for _ in range(15):\n",
    "        mid = (lo + hi) / 2.0\n",
    "        if received_db(self.noise_db, mid) > 118:\n",
    "            lo = mid\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            hi = mid\n",
    "    return lo"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Ship Movement\n",
    "\n",
    "Each frame the ship slides toward its lane position using linear interpolation. The expression \n",
    "(self.lane - self.x) * dt * 4 moves the ship a fraction of the remaining distance each frame, \n",
    "producing a smooth easing effect. The wake trail stores the last 22 positions to draw the wake behind the ship. \n",
    "When the ship exits the bottom of the screen, finished is set to True and the main loop respawns it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def update(self):\n",
    "    if self.finished:\n",
    "        return\n",
    "    if not self.being_dragged:\n",
    "        self.x += (self.lane - self.x) * (1/60) * 4  # slide toward lane smoothly\n",
    "        self.y += self.speed * (1/60) * 60\n",
    "    self.wake_trail.append((int(self.x), int(self.y)))\n",
    "    if len(self.wake_trail) > 22:\n",
    "        self.wake_trail.pop(0)\n",
    "    if self.y > height + 40:\n",
    "        self.finished = True"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Slowing Ships Down\n",
    "\n",
    "toggle_slow switches the ship between full speed and 28% of its base speed. \n",
    "Reducing speed to 0.28x brings the noise down from 168 dB to around 101 dB at the source, \n",
    "which is below the 118 dB whale masking threshold at typical crossing distances. \n",
    "The is_slow flag is used by the draw method to turn the ship amber so the player can see which ships are slowed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def toggle_slow(self):\n",
    "    self.is_slow = not self.is_slow\n",
    "    self.speed = self.base_speed * (0.28 if self.is_slow else 1.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Drawing Ships\n",
    "\n",
    "Each ship is drawn as a simple polygon representing a hull viewed from above, pointing downward. \n",
    "The color shifts to AMBER when the ship is slowed to give the player clear visual feedback. \n",
    "The wake trail is drawn first with increasing opacity toward the ship. \n",
    "A small circle at the center represents the navigation light."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def draw(self):\n",
    "    if self.finished:\n",
    "        return\n",
    "    for i, (wx, wy) in enumerate(self.wake_trail):\n",
    "        alpha = int(38 * i / max(len(self.wake_trail), 1))\n",
    "        s = pygame.Surface((4, 4), pygame.SRCALPHA)\n",
    "        pygame.draw.circle(s, (*FOAM, alpha), (2, 2), 2)\n",
    "        win.blit(s, (wx - 2, wy - 2))\n",
    "    cx, cy = int(self.x), int(self.y)\n",
    "    col = AMBER if self.is_slow else (85, 92, 105)\n",
    "    hull = [(cx, cy-16), (cx+9, cy-5), (cx+7, cy+12), (cx-7, cy+12), (cx-9, cy-5)]\n",
    "    pygame.draw.polygon(win, col, hull)\n",
    "    pygame.draw.polygon(win, (190, 196, 206), hull, 1)\n",
    "    pygame.draw.rect(win, (100, 106, 118), (cx-4, cy-5, 8, 13))\n",
    "    pygame.draw.circle(win, (252, 234, 168), (cx, cy), 3)  # nav light\n",
    "    if self.is_slow:\n",
    "        lb = font3.render(\"SLOW\", True, AMBER)\n",
    "        win.blit(lb, (cx - lb.get_width() // 2, cy - 30))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Whale Class\n",
    "\n",
    "The Whale class represents a whale pod traveling left to right across the ocean. \n",
    "Each whale has a target lane_y it tries to stay close to while swimming toward the right edge. \n",
    "The stress attribute is the core mechanic -- it ranges from 0.0 (completely calm) to 1.0 (maximum stress). \n",
    "Above 0.55, the whale becomes lost and starts wandering randomly. Above 0.72, it can strand if it hits a boundary. \n",
    "whale_count is a class variable that tracks the total number created."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class Whale:\n",
    "    whale_count = 0\n",
    "    def __init__(self, lane_y, start_x=None):\n",
    "        self.lane_y = float(lane_y)\n",
    "        self.x = float(start_x if start_x is not None else -1 * random.randint(20, 60))\n",
    "        self.y = float(lane_y + random.randint(-12, 12))\n",
    "        self.vx = 0.0\n",
    "        self.vy = 0.0\n",
    "        self.stress = 0.0\n",
    "        self.is_lost = False\n",
    "        self.is_safe = False\n",
    "        self.is_stranded = False\n",
    "        self.wander_angle = 0.0\n",
    "        self.trail  = []\n",
    "        self.counted_strand = False\n",
    "        self.counted_safe = False\n",
    "        Whale.whale_count+= 1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Calculating Total Noise Exposure\n",
    "\n",
    "A whale's total noise exposure comes from all five ships simultaneously. You cannot simply average decibel values \n",
    "because dB is a logarithmic scale. Instead, each ship's received dB is converted to linear acoustic intensity \n",
    "using \\\\(I = 10^{dB/10}\\\\), all intensities are summed, then converted back to dB using \\\\(dB = 10 \\cdot \\log_{10}(I_{total})\\\\). \n",
    "This is called acoustic superposition and is the correct way to combine multiple noise sources."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def get_noise_level(self, ships):\n",
    "    total_intensity = 0.0\n",
    "    for s in ships:\n",
    "        if s.finished:\n",
    "            continue\n",
    "        dist = math.sqrt((self.x - s.x)**2 + (self.y - s.y)**2)\n",
    "        db = received_db(s.noise_db, dist)\n",
    "        total_intensity += 10.0 ** (db / 10.0)  # convert to linear intensity\n",
    "    return 10.0 * math.log10(total_intensity) if total_intensity > 0 else 0.0"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Whale Movement and Stress System\n",
    "\n",
    "Each frame, the whale calculates its noise level and updates its stress accordingly. \n",
    "Above 118 dB, stress builds at 0.07 per second. Between 100 and 118 dB, it builds slowly at 0.01 per second. \n",
    "Below 100 dB it recovers at 0.12 per second. These rates were tuned so players have roughly 15 seconds \n",
    "to react before a whale becomes lost.\n",
    "\n",
    "When calm, the whale swims toward the right edge with a gentle y-correction back to its lane. \n",
    "The 0.28 multiplier on the y-correction keeps the movement smooth rather than snapping rigidly to the lane. \n",
    "When lost, the wander angle updates with random Gaussian noise scaled by the current stress level, \n",
    "so more stressed whales wander more erratically."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def move(self, ships):\n",
    "    if self.is_stranded or self.is_safe:\n",
    "        return\n",
    "\n",
    "    noise = self.get_noise_level(ships)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if noise > 118:\n",
    "        self.stress = min(1.0, self.stress + (1/60) * 0.07)\n",
    "    elif noise > 100:\n",
    "        self.stress = min(1.0, self.stress + (1/60) * 0.01)\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        self.stress = max(0.0, self.stress - (1/60) * 0.12)\n",
    "\n",
    "    self.is_lost = self.stress > 0.55\n",
    "\n",
    "    if self.is_lost:\n",
    "        chaos = 0.5 + self.stress\n",
    "        self.wander_angle += random.gauss(0, dt * chaos)  # wilder when more stressed\n",
    "        self.wander_angle  = max(-1.3, min(1.3, self.wander_angle))\n",
    "        target_vx = math.cos(self.wander_angle) * 0.44\n",
    "        target_vy = math.sin(self.wander_angle) * 0.44\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        dx = (OCEAN_W + 10) - self.x\n",
    "        dy = self.lane_y - self.y\n",
    "        dist = math.sqrt(dx**2 + dy**2) + 0.001\n",
    "        target_vx = (dx / dist) * 0.47\n",
    "        target_vy = (dy / dist) * 0.47 * 0.28  # ycorrection\n",
    "\n",
    "    smooth = min(1.0, (1/60) * 3.5)\n",
    "    self.vx += (target_vx - self.vx) * smooth\n",
    "    self.vy += (target_vy - self.vy) * smooth\n",
    "    self.x  += self.vx\n",
    "    self.y  += self.vy\n",
    "\n",
    "    edge = 18\n",
    "    if self.stress > 0.72 and self.is_lost:\n",
    "        if self.y < edge or self.y > height - edge or self.x < edge:\n",
    "            self.is_stranded = True\n",
    "            return\n",
    "\n",
    "    self.y = max(edge, min(height - edge, self.y))\n",
    "    self.x = max(-80, self.x)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if self.x > OCEAN_W - 8:\n",
    "        self.is_safe = True\n",
    "        return\n",
    "\n",
    "    self.trail.append((int(self.x), int(self.y)))\n",
    "    if len(self.trail) > 38:\n",
    "        self.trail.pop(0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Drawing Whales\n",
    "\n",
    "The whale is drawn as a series of polygons rotated to face the direction of travel. \n",
    "math.atan2 calculates the angle from the velocity vector, and rotation is applied using standard \n",
    "2D rotation math: the rot helper rotates any point (px, py) around the whale center.\n",
    "\n",
    "The body color shifts from dark teal-gray toward red as stress increases, giving visual feedback \n",
    "that matches the stress bar. The stress bar itself transitions from green through yellow to red \n",
    "using linear interpolation between color values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def draw(self):\n",
    "    cx, cy = int(self.x), int(self.y)\n",
    "    ang = math.atan2(self.vy, self.vx) if (self.vx or self.vy) else 0\n",
    "    ca, sa = math.cos(ang), math.sin(ang)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def rot(px, py):  # rotate point around whale center\n",
    "        return (cx + int(px*ca - py*sa), cy + int(px*sa + py*ca))\n",
    "\n",
    "    bc = (min(255, int(50 + self.stress*60)),\n",
    "          max(0,int(72 - self.stress*26)),\n",
    "          max(0,int(92 - self.stress*30)))  # gets redder when strssed\n",
    "\n",
    "    pygame.draw.polygon(win, bc, [rot(-25,0), rot(-18,7), rot(-14,3), rot(-14,-3), rot(-18,-7)])# tail\n",
    "    pygame.draw.polygon(win, bc, [rot(24,0), rot(14,7), rot(0,9), rot(-12,7), rot(-24,0),\n",
    "                                   rot(-12,-7), rot(0,-9), rot(14,-7)]) # body\n",
    "    pygame.draw.polygon(win, (112, 138, 155), [rot(16,0), rot(7,4), rot(-6,5),\n",
    "                                                rot(-14,0), rot(-6,-5), rot(7,-4)])# belly\n",
    "\n",
    "    # stress bar\n",
    "    bw = 34\n",
    "    bx = cx - bw // 2\n",
    "    by = cy - 32\n",
    "    t = (self.stress / 0.5) if self.stress < 0.5 else (self.stress - 0.5) / 0.5\n",
    "    c1 = GREEN if self.stress < 0.5 else YELLOW\n",
    "    c2 = YELLOW if self.stress < 0.5 else RED\n",
    "    bar_col = tuple(int(c1[i] + (c2[i] - c1[i]) * t) for i in range(3))\n",
    "    fw = int(bw * self.stress)\n",
    "    if fw > 0:\n",
    "        pygame.draw.rect(win, bar_col, (bx, by, fw, 5), border_radius=2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Noise Ring Visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "The expanding rings around each ship make the acoustic physics visible. Three rings expand outward \n",
    "simultaneously at different phases, creating a continuous pulse animation. Each ring's radius at any \n",
    "given moment is a fraction of the total danger radius, and its color is determined by how loud the noise \n",
    "is at that distance. Red means the noise level is still above 125 dB at that radius, yellow between 110 and 125, \n",
    "and green below 110. All rings are drawn onto an SRCALPHA surface so they can be transparent."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def draw_noise_rings(ships, t):\n",
    "    ring_surf = pygame.Surface((OCEAN_W, height), pygame.SRCALPHA)\n",
    "    for s in ships:\n",
    "        if s.finished:\n",
    "            continue\n",
    "        dr = s.get_danger_radius()\n",
    "        for i in range(3):\n",
    "            phase = ((t * 0.45) + i * 0.333) % 1.0\n",
    "            rad = phase * dr\n",
    "            if rad < 4:\n",
    "                continue\n",
    "            alpha = int(72 * (1.0 - phase))  # fades as it expands\n",
    "            db_here = received_db(s.noise_db, rad)\n",
    "            ring_col = RED if db_here > 125 else YELLOW if db_here > 110 else GREEN\n",
    "            pygame.draw.circle(ring_surf, (*ring_col, alpha), (int(s.x), int(s.y)), int(rad), 2)\n",
    "    win.blit(ring_surf, (0, 0))"
   ]
